=E2=80=9C=E2=80=98It=E2=80=99s the first European war in the ESG age,=E2=80=
=99 says Steven Fox, chief executive of the strategic intelligence group Ve=
racity Worldwide=E2=80=9D to the Financial Times. He is talking specificall=
y about a decision by Levi Strauss & Co. to pull out of the Russian market =
following Russia=E2=80=99s invasion of Ukraine, and more broadly about deci=
sions by lots of international companies to pull out of Russia to protest t=
he invasion, or to comply with sanctions, or to avoid the risk and uncertai=
nty and bad publicity of staying in Russia. It is quite a line. In the olde=
n days =E2=80=94=C2=A010 years ago? =E2=80=94=C2=A0big public companies wer=
e essentially in the business of maximizing cash flows for shareholders; th=
ey might pull out of a war zone to avoid risk, but you would not expect eve=
ry public company to take a moral stand on every important issue. In the ne=
w world of environmental, social and governance investing, companies are ex=
pected to be moral actors.More specifically, in the new world of ESG=C2=A0a=
nd the invasion of Ukraine, companies have to think about three competing g=
oals:=09Make money for shareholders.=09Do stuff that was ESG a month ago, m=
eaning a certain amount of social and governance stuff but=C2=A0primarily=
=C2=A0reducing carbon emissions.=09Be patriotic participants in Ukraine=E2=
=80=99s, and the world=E2=80=99s, defense against Russian invasion.In many =
cases, Things 2 and 3 push in the same direction: Russia=E2=80=99s ability =
to wage war is funded by oil and gas exports,=C2=A0its war effort is helped=
 by high oil and gas prices, so reducing the use of oil and gas is=C2=A0bot=
h=C2=A0good for the environment=C2=A0and=C2=A0good for Ukraine.There are no=
table exceptions, though, particularly for oil and gas companies. If you=E2=
=80=99re an oil company, opening lots of marginal projects to drill lots of=
 oil is=C2=A0bad=C2=A0for the environment, and something that your ESG-focu=
sed shareholders disliked a month ago, but it also reduces oil prices and s=
o is=C2=A0good=C2=A0for Ukraine.=C2=A0And so on the one hand oil producers =
get ESG-ish patriotic pressure to increase drilling, even at the cost of sh=
areholder returns:The Biden administration has ratcheted up pressure on US =
shale producers, telling them they should be doing =E2=80=9Cwhatever it tak=
es=E2=80=9D to increase supply and tame oil prices that have soared followi=
ng Vladimir Putin=E2=80=99s invasion of Ukraine.Amos Hochstein, the state d=
epartment=E2=80=99s special envoy and co-ordinator for international energy=
 affairs, dismissed as =E2=80=9Cnonsense=E2=80=9D industry claims that Whit=
e House policies are holding back drilling and instead blamed Wall Street i=
nvestors he said were hungry for returns. =E2=80=A6=E2=80=9CIf there=E2=80=
=99s anyone that=E2=80=99s standing in the way, according to them, it=E2=80=
=99s their financial backers, who are insisting on dividends and fiscal dis=
cipline in the face of a war in Europe, and the highest prices we have seen=
 in a couple of generations,=E2=80=9D Hochstein told the Financial Times in=
 an interview on the sidelines of the CERAWeek energy conference in Houston=
.Hochstein added: =E2=80=9CAnd that=E2=80=99s not a US government problem. =
If there=E2=80=99s a bottleneck it is on Wall Street. They should call thei=
r financiers and tell them there=E2=80=99s a war going on. The American pub=
lic is paying the price.=E2=80=9DAnd on the other hand companies=C2=A0still=
 get ESG-ish environmental pressure to reduce drilling, even at the cost of=
 shareholder returns:Credit Suisse is facing shareholder calls to cut its f=
ossil fuel exposure while a new study has revealed European companies=E2=80=
=99 slow progress on emissions, as pressure mounts on the corporate world t=
o step up its climate efforts.Investors with =E2=82=AC2.2tn under managemen=
t filed a resolution at the Swiss bank on Wednesday calling for it to slash=
 its exposure to oil, gas and coal assets. =E2=80=A6Credit Suisse has lent =
more than $82bn to fossil fuel companies and projects since the 2016 signin=
g of the Paris agreement and is Europe=E2=80=99s top bank for the provision=
 of coal mining finance, according to the two charities. =E2=80=A6Rob Baile=
y, partner at Oliver Wyman, said he expected to see the emissions-cutting r=
ate =E2=80=9Cstart to improve=E2=80=9D as companies move from focusing on s=
etting targets to implementing them.Maxfield Weiss, executive director at C=
DP Europe, said if investors could take =E2=80=9Csuper fast action in the f=
ace of crises=E2=80=9D such as the Ukraine war, it =E2=80=9Craises a questi=
on=E2=80=9D about whether companies and financial institutions were acting =
fast enough to tackle climate change.Tell them there=E2=80=99s a war going =
on!The old-school theory of corporate finance, in which the duty of a publi=
c company is to maximize shareholder value, was not really about this being=
 the=C2=A0best=C2=A0goal; rather, it was about the clarity=C2=A0of having=
=C2=A0one=C2=A0goal. It is not always obvious what a company should do to m=
aximize shareholder value, but it is more or less obvious when a company ha=
s succeeded (the stock goes up). With ESG, that is not true: Different shar=
eholders, stakeholders, governments, etc., could have different views about=
 what is good for the environment, governance or (particularly) society. =
=E2=80=9CDo what is good for shareholder value=E2=80=9D does not exactly te=
ll executives what to do, but it does=C2=A0hold them to account=C2=A0for do=
ing it. =E2=80=9CDo what is good for society=E2=80=9D does not really do ev=
en that. Is it good for society to drill more oil to keep oil prices down, =
or to drill less oil to keep emissions down?=C2=A0Meanwhile, we  talked las=
t week about how producing military weapons was not especially ESG, but has=
 now, given the increased risk of Russian aggression against Europe, become=
 much more ESG. But  not entirely ESG:Hundreds of ESG funds run by some of =
the world=E2=80=99s biggest money managers have a combined $13.4 billion st=
ake in companies that supply weapons and technology to the Myanmar military=
, according to a report.The funds, which say they take into account environ=
mental, social and governance risks, have investments across 33 companies t=
hat the United Nations and two advocacy groups say provided weapons, commun=
ications and technologies to the military, Inclusive Development Internatio=
nal and ALTSEAN-Burma said in a report released Wednesday. ...At the same t=
ime, some analysts and investors are making a new case for the defense indu=
stry and military technologies on moral or political grounds, as a measure =
of support for companies that supply the Ukrainian army.=C2=A0David Pred, e=
xecutive director of Inclusive Development International, said there=E2=80=
=99s no place for arms manufacturers in ESG funds, =E2=80=9Cfull stop.=E2=
=80=9D=C2=A0=E2=80=9CAnd certainly not companies that supply regimes that a=
re using those weapons on innocent civilians and for non-defensive purposes=
,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CFor us, it is about the human impact of the co=
mpany and its product, there=E2=80=99s just no reasonable argument for arms=
 makers to be in these funds.=E2=80=9DIf you are an ESG investor you need t=
o have a theory of international relations that tells you whether it is a n=
et=C2=A0good or bad for human flourishing for democracies to procure powerf=
ul weapons to deter and/or conduct wars. If you were a non-ESG investor you=
 just had to know if companies could sell the weapons at a profit. But you =
can=E2=80=99t do that anymore. Even if you care only about money, now ESG i=
nforms both what companies will do and how markets will react. It=E2=80=99s=
 the ESG age now.
