   =20
      Good timing
   =20
 =20
One kind of trading that you could do is betting on which companies will be=
 acquired. You identify a company, you think =E2=80=9Cthis company is ripe =
for a takeover at a premium,=E2=80=9D and you buy its stock hoping that you=
=E2=80=99re right. Or, even better, you buy=C2=A0call options=C2=A0on the c=
ompany, to make a levered bet that there will be a takeover soon,=C2=A0befo=
re your options expire.=C2=A0People do this, it=E2=80=99s a thing, but it s=
trikes me as a somewhat unpleasant business? There are basically two possib=
le outcomes:=09You are wrong and lose money.=09You are right and make money=
, but everyone is like =E2=80=9Cboy it is=C2=A0pretty suspicious=C2=A0that =
you bought all these call options right before a takeover was announced=E2=
=80=9D and you get investigated for insider trading.Also honestly if you ar=
e good at this =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you are right a lot =E2=80=94=C2=A0it is p=
robably because you cultivate the sorts of relationships and gossip network=
s that will make people extra suspicious about your good timing?=C2=A0Anywa=
y:Federal prosecutors and securities regulators are investigating large bet=
s that Barry Diller, Alexander von Furstenberg and David Geffen made on Act=
ivision Blizzard Inc. shares in January, days before the videogame maker ag=
reed to be acquired by Microsoft Corp., according to people familiar with t=
he matter. =E2=80=A6Messrs. Diller, von Furstenberg and Geffen bought optio=
ns to purchase Activision shares at $40 each on Jan. 14 in privately arrang=
ed transactions through JPMorgan Chase & Co., the people said. Activision s=
hares were trading around $63 at the time, meaning the options were already=
 profitable to exercise, or =E2=80=9Cin the money.=E2=80=9D Option holders =
could reap more if Activision=E2=80=99s stock price rose.Mr. Diller said in=
 an interview that none of the men had material nonpublic information about=
 the Microsoft-Activision deal. He confirmed they had been contacted by reg=
ulators.=E2=80=9CIt was simply a lucky bet,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CWe a=
cted on no information of any kind from anyone. It is one of those coincide=
nces.=E2=80=9D ...The three men haven=E2=80=99t yet exercised the options, =
which don=E2=80=99t expire until early next year, the people said.The trade=
rs appear to have spent around $108 million to acquire the right to buy 4.1=
2 million Activision shares, the people said. Those options are now valued =
at around $168 million, based on recent trading prices. The value of the op=
tions would rise further if the deal closes at the stated per-share price o=
f $95, which Microsoft has said is expected after midyear. If the men hold =
the options through a closing at that price, their profit stands to surpass=
 $100 million, the people said.=C2=A0Mr. Diller has served on the board of =
directors of Coca-Cola Co. with Activision Chief Executive Bobby Kotick.=C2=
=A0Just one of those things! I mean. The thing is that if Bobby Kotick call=
ed you up and said =E2=80=9Chey we=E2=80=99re doing a merger in four days=
=E2=80=9D and you bought call options you=E2=80=99d be whisked off to jail =
immediately; these people seem smart and well-advised so I am going to assu=
me that =E2=80=9Csimply a lucky bet=E2=80=9D is the correct explanation.[1]=
 Still. Arguably too lucky. So lucky that it=E2=80=99s unlucky.My favorite =
part of this might be that these are not listed options that you can buy=C2=
=A0on the exchange, but rather over-the-counter options that they negotiate=
d directly with JPMorgan Chase & Co. I don=E2=80=99t know how JPMorgan hedg=
ed the options that it sold, but ordinarily you would expect that a bank se=
lling options like this would=C2=A0lose money if the stock shot up due to a=
 merger announcement. Not so=C2=A0much money, given how they were probably =
hedged =E2=80=94=C2=A0certainly not the $60 million that these guys made =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0but perhaps a few million dollars.[2] If you are a trader at=
 a bank and the salesperson covering rich well-connected entertainment-indu=
stry clients comes to you and says =E2=80=9Chey I need to buy $108 million =
of options for my guys, this is a great trade for us,=E2=80=9D and you quot=
e a price and sell those options, and then=C2=A0four days later=C2=A0there=
=E2=80=99s a merger announcement and you take a loss, you will be mad. You =
will go over to the salesperson and complain. You will want to know what th=
e buyers knew and when they knew it.=C2=A0You will perhaps want revenge. Yo=
u will perhaps get it:JPMorgan reported the trades to law enforcement after=
 the deal became public, the people said. Under the terms of a criminal set=
tlement it reached in September 2020 related to market-manipulation claims,=
 JPMorgan is required to disclose to law enforcement evidence or concerns a=
bout misconduct over the duration of the three-year agreement. JPMorgan dec=
lined to comment.=E2=80=9CSorry, I=E2=80=99m required to report this to the=
 Feds, nothing I can do about it,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0you say through clenched te=
eth.
 =20
   =20
      Tim Leissner!
   =20
 =20
Tim Leissner is a former Goldman Sachs Group Inc. banker who  did a ton of =
crimes in connection with the looting of Malaysian development fund 1MDB. H=
e has pleaded guilty and is cooperating with prosecutors who are trying his=
 former subordinate, Roger Ng, for allegedly assisting him with some of tho=
se crimes. Leissner has been testifying at Ng's trial, and recently Ng=E2=
=80=99s lawyers have been cross-examining him to try to undermine his testi=
mony. This seems to consist mostly of asking him about all the times he lie=
d, in order to suggest to the jury that he=E2=80=99s probably lying now.Thi=
s is going to take a while, because Leissner seems to have been one of the =
most astonishing liars in the modern financial industry. We have  talked be=
fore about how he=C2=A0twice faked divorces=C2=A0to marry other women;  now=
 here=E2=80=99s this:Ex-Goldman Sachs star banker Tim Leissner detailed Tue=
sday how he used an email account with his ex-wife=E2=80=99s name for all s=
orts of shenanigans, beginning with a lie to his girlfriend at the time, Ki=
mora Lee Simmons.=C2=A0Posing as his then-wife Judy Chan, Leissner initiall=
y used the account to try to convince Simmons the two were no longer marrie=
d. But he went on to pose as Chan for years to converse with Simmons about =
family vacations and other topics. ...Leissner was questioned Tuesday about=
 the phony email account by Ng=E2=80=99s lawyer, Marc Agnifilo, who=E2=80=
=99s trying to undermine the banker=E2=80=99s credibility by showing the ju=
ry that he=E2=80=99s a =E2=80=9Crare cunning liar,=E2=80=9D as the attorney=
 told the judge.While posing as Chan, Leissner declined Simmons=E2=80=99s r=
epeated invitations for Chan and her children to vacation with the former m=
odel and her family in Paris, an Austrian ski holiday and a private Caribbe=
an island. In one email created by Leissner, Chan told Simmons she=E2=80=99=
d be unable to visit because she and her children with Leissner had been in=
jured in a car accident.=E2=80=9CIt was an entire life you completely falsi=
fied because you made the whole thing up?=E2=80=9D an incredulous Agnifilo =
asked.=E2=80=9CThe correspondence yes,=E2=80=9D Leissner said. =E2=80=9CBut=
 an entire life may be too far.=E2=80=9D =C2=A0=E2=80=9CSure like 90% of my=
 life was fake, but 100%? That seems high.=E2=80=9D I am not sure how much =
prosecutors really=C2=A0need=C2=A0Leissner=E2=80=99s testimony; the looting=
 of 1MDB was  pretty egregious, and=C2=A0presumably there is documentary ev=
idence of Ng's participation. It=E2=80=99s plausible that the jury could (1=
) conclude that Leissner is lying about everything he says but (2) convict =
Ng anyway. I wouldn=E2=80=99t, though. I am offended that prosecutors put t=
his serial liar=C2=A0on the stand to testify against his surely-not-nearly-=
as-bad underling, and if I were on the jury I=E2=80=99d  acquit on principl=
e.=C2=A0Also it continues to amaze me that this guy was a Goldman Sachs Gro=
up Inc. partner. (Disclosure, I used to work at Goldman.) I feel like there=
 is a sort of oscillating hierarchy of honesty in investment banking:=09If =
you are perfectly honest, that will limit your career. =E2=80=9CDon=E2=80=
=99t do this merger,=E2=80=9D you will say to clients, too often.=C2=A0=09I=
f you are a reasonable amount of dishonest =E2=80=94=C2=A0honest, but with =
some caveats =E2=80=94=C2=A0then you are what people call =E2=80=9Ccommerci=
al,=E2=80=9D the highest praise for an investment banker, and you will go f=
ar.=C2=A0The job involves getting clients to do deals and pay you large fee=
s, and that calls for a certain ability to feign enthusiasm, misdirect atte=
ntion, etc. Sure=C2=A0you should never=C2=A0lie=C2=A0to clients, but you mi=
ght=C2=A0want to choose what to emphasize in ways that help the=C2=A0bottom=
 line.=09If you are=C2=A0too=C2=A0dishonest, that will again limit your car=
eer: A banker who lies to clients, or to colleagues, is a=C2=A0regulatory a=
nd reputational risk; Goldman, at least, retains enough of its old partners=
hip culture that no one will want a partner whom they can=E2=80=99t trust.=
=09If you are=C2=A0incredibly, absurdly=C2=A0dishonest then I guess you get=
=C2=A0good at it and can convince all the partners that you=E2=80=99re actu=
ally honest enough to make partner? Those are the really risky ones.
