<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">ESG</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9C=E2=80=98It=E2=80=99s the fir=
st European war in the ESG age,=E2=80=99 says Steven Fox, chief executive o=
f the strategic intelligence group Veracity Worldwide=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26966673.261607/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvMDg3ZmNiM2QtZDVjYi00NWU3LTg0ZGYtMzBhOTAyMGNhMTAz/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB51e920ba" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">to the Financial Times</a>. He is ta=
lking specifically about a decision by Levi Strauss &amp; Co. to pull out o=
f the Russian market following Russia=E2=80=99s invasion of Ukraine, and mo=
re broadly about decisions by lots of international companies to pull out o=
f Russia to protest the invasion, or to comply with sanctions, or to avoid =
the risk and uncertainty and bad publicity of staying in Russia. It is quit=
e a line. In the olden days =E2=80=94=C2=A010 years ago? =E2=80=94=C2=A0big=
 public companies were essentially in the business of maximizing cash flows=
 for shareholders; they might pull out of a war zone to avoid risk, but you=
 would not expect every public company to take a moral stand on every impor=
tant issue. In the new world of environmental, social and governance invest=
ing, companies are expected to be moral actors.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">More specifically, in the new world of ESG=C2=A0<em>and the invasion o=
f Ukraine</em>, companies have to think about three competing goals:</p><ol=
 style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Make money for shareholders.</li>=09<l=
i style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Do stuff that was ESG a month ago, meaning =
a certain amount of social and governance stuff but=C2=A0<em>primarily=C2=
=A0</em>reducing carbon emissions.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"=
>Be patriotic participants in Ukraine=E2=80=99s, and the world=E2=80=99s, d=
efense against Russian invasion.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In m=
any cases, Things 2 and 3 push in the same direction: Russia=E2=80=99s abil=
ity to wage war is funded by oil and gas exports,=C2=A0its war effort is he=
lped by high oil and gas prices, so reducing the use of oil and gas is=C2=
=A0<em>both=C2=A0</em>good for the environment=C2=A0<em>and=C2=A0</em>good =
for Ukraine.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are notable exceptions, =
though, particularly for oil and gas companies. If you=E2=80=99re an oil co=
mpany, opening lots of marginal projects to drill lots of oil is=C2=A0<em>b=
ad=C2=A0</em>for the environment, and something that your ESG-focused share=
holders disliked a month ago, but it also reduces oil prices and so is=C2=
=A0<em>good=C2=A0</em>for Ukraine.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An=
d so on the one hand oil producers get ESG-ish <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26966673.261607/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2Nvbn=
RlbnQvZmVlODhlODAtOGJhOS00YWI4LTlkNzktY2JkOTIzNWRkMjli/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cBf10bb053" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;">patriotic pressure to increase drilling</a>, even at=
 the cost of shareholder returns:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">The Biden administration has ratcheted up pressure on US shale producers=
, telling them they should be doing =E2=80=9Cwhatever it takes=E2=80=9D to =
increase supply and tame oil prices that have soared following Vladimir Put=
in=E2=80=99s invasion of Ukraine.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Amos Hoch=
stein, the state department=E2=80=99s special envoy and co-ordinator for in=
ternational energy affairs, dismissed as =E2=80=9Cnonsense=E2=80=9D industr=
y claims that White House policies are holding back drilling and instead bl=
amed Wall Street investors he said were hungry for returns. =E2=80=A6</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIf there=E2=80=99s anyone that=E2=80=99=
s standing in the way, according to them, it=E2=80=99s their financial back=
ers, who are insisting on dividends and fiscal discipline in the face of a =
war in Europe, and the highest prices we have seen in a couple of generatio=
ns,=E2=80=9D Hochstein told the Financial Times in an interview on the side=
lines of the CERAWeek energy conference in Houston.</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">Hochstein added: =E2=80=9CAnd that=E2=80=99s not a US government p=
roblem. If there=E2=80=99s a bottleneck it is on Wall Street. They should c=
all their financiers and tell them there=E2=80=99s a war going on. The Amer=
ican public is paying the price.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">And on the other hand companies=C2=A0still get ESG-ish <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26966673.261607/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvYTg4NTIzMmUtNGE0ZS00MzhhLWIyODUtY2NlMTJhMWE3YzBj=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB36aa75be" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">environmental pressure to reduc=
e drilling</a>, even at the cost of shareholder returns:</p><blockquote><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Credit Suisse is facing shareholder calls to cut =
its fossil fuel exposure while a new study has revealed European companies=
=E2=80=99 slow progress on emissions, as pressure mounts on the corporate w=
orld to step up its climate efforts.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Invest=
ors with =E2=82=AC2.2tn under management filed a resolution at the Swiss ba=
nk on Wednesday calling for it to slash its exposure to oil, gas and coal a=
ssets. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Credit Suisse has lent mor=
e than $82bn to fossil fuel companies and projects since the 2016 signing o=
f the Paris agreement and is Europe=E2=80=99s top bank for the provision of=
 coal mining finance, according to the two charities. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Rob Bailey, partner at Oliver Wyman, said he expected =
to see the emissions-cutting rate =E2=80=9Cstart to improve=E2=80=9D as com=
panies move from focusing on setting targets to implementing them.</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Maxfield Weiss, executive director at CDP Europe, s=
aid if investors could take =E2=80=9Csuper fast action in the face of crise=
s=E2=80=9D such as the Ukraine war, it =E2=80=9Craises a question=E2=80=9D =
about whether companies and financial institutions were acting fast enough =
to tackle climate change.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Tell=
 them there=E2=80=99s a war going on!</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The o=
ld-school theory of corporate finance, in which the duty of a public compan=
y is to maximize shareholder value, was not really about this being the=C2=
=A0<em>best=C2=A0</em>goal; rather, it was about the clarity=C2=A0of having=
=C2=A0<em>one=C2=A0</em>goal. It is not always obvious what a company shoul=
d do to maximize shareholder value, but it is more or less obvious when a c=
ompany has succeeded (the stock goes up). With ESG, that is not true: Diffe=
rent shareholders, stakeholders, governments, etc., could have different vi=
ews about what is good for the environment, governance or (particularly) so=
ciety. =E2=80=9CDo what is good for shareholder value=E2=80=9D does not exa=
ctly tell executives what to do, but it does=C2=A0<em>hold them to account=
=C2=A0</em>for doing it. =E2=80=9CDo what is good for society=E2=80=9D does=
 not really do even that. Is it good for society to drill more oil to keep =
oil prices down, or to drill less oil to keep emissions down?=C2=A0</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile, we <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/26966673.261607/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcG=
luaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMDEvbm9ib2R5LXdhbnRzLXJ1c3NpYW4tYXNzZXRzP2Ntc=
GlkPUJCRDAzMDkyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdz=
bGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDMwOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cBbb251eba" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked last week</a> about how producing mi=
litary weapons was not especially ESG, but has now, given the increased ris=
k of Russian aggression against Europe, become much more ESG. But <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26966673.261607/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMDkvZXNnLWludmVzdG9y=
cy1ob2xkLTEzLTQtYmlsbGlvbi1pbi1teWFubWFyLW1pbGl0YXJ5LXN1cHBsaWVycz9jbXBpZD1=
CQkQwMzA5MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldH=
RlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjAzMDkmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cBa5e66bed" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;"> not entirely ESG</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">Hundreds of ESG funds run by some of the world=E2=80=99s =
biggest money managers have a combined $13.4 billion stake in companies tha=
t supply weapons and technology to the Myanmar military, according to a rep=
ort.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The funds, which say they take into ac=
count environmental, social and governance risks, have investments across 3=
3 companies that the United Nations and two advocacy groups say provided we=
apons, communications and technologies to the military, Inclusive Developme=
nt International and ALTSEAN-Burma said in a report released Wednesday. ...=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At the same time, some analysts and invest=
ors are making a new case for the defense industry and military technologie=
s on moral or political grounds, as a measure of support for companies that=
 supply the Ukrainian army.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">David Pre=
d, executive director of Inclusive Development International, said there=E2=
=80=99s no place for arms manufacturers in ESG funds, =E2=80=9Cfull stop.=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CAnd certainly not =
companies that supply regimes that are using those weapons on innocent civi=
lians and for non-defensive purposes,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CFor us, it=
 is about the human impact of the company and its product, there=E2=80=99s =
just no reasonable argument for arms makers to be in these funds.=E2=80=9D<=
/p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are an ESG investor you=
 need to have a theory of international relations that tells you whether it=
 is a net=C2=A0good or bad for human flourishing for democracies to procure=
 powerful weapons to deter and/or conduct wars. If you were a non-ESG inves=
tor you just had to know if companies could sell the weapons at a profit. B=
ut you can=E2=80=99t do that anymore. Even if you care only about money, no=
w ESG informs both what companies will do and how markets will react. It=E2=
=80=99s the ESG age now.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-sponsored-content" w=
idth=3D"auto" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0">
