</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One kind of trading that you could do =
is betting on which companies will be acquired. You identify a company, you=
 think =E2=80=9Cthis company is ripe for a takeover at a premium,=E2=80=9D =
and you buy its stock hoping that you=E2=80=99re right. Or, even better, yo=
u buy=C2=A0<em>call options=C2=A0</em>on the company, to make a levered bet=
 that there will be a takeover <em>soon</em>,<em>=C2=A0</em>before your opt=
ions expire.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">People do this, it=E2=80=
=99s a thing, but it strikes me as a somewhat unpleasant business? There ar=
e basically two possible outcomes:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal=
; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"=
>You are wrong and lose money.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You=
 are right and make money, but everyone is like =E2=80=9Cboy it is=C2=A0<em=
>pretty suspicious=C2=A0</em>that you bought all these call options right b=
efore a takeover was announced=E2=80=9D and you get investigated for inside=
r trading.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also honestly if you are g=
ood at this =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you are right a lot =E2=80=94=C2=A0it is prob=
ably because you cultivate the sorts of relationships and gossip networks t=
hat will make people extra suspicious about your good timing?=C2=A0<a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26966673.261607/aHR0cHM6L=
